  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically covered under criminal legislation. Specifically:\n\n1. Legal Classification\n- Money laundering is considered a serious financial crime\n- It involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Prosecuted under criminal statutes and laws\n\n2. Legal Frameworks\n- Many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Regulated by criminal codes and financial crime legislation\n- Involves criminal investigations and potential criminal prosecution\n\n3. Potential Penalties\n- Can include significant fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal record\n\n4. International Cooperation\n- Most countries have laws addressing money laundering\n- International treaties and agreements support cross-border enforcement\n- Organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) provide global guidelines\n\n5. Common Legal Approaches\n- Criminalizing the process of disguising illegal funds\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing legal mechanisms to trace and prosecute offenders\n\nMoney laundering is universally treated as a criminal offense due to its connection with other serious criminal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, and organized crime.",
